On Patriot Day, President Donald Trump issued a proclamation to honor the victims of the September 11, 2001 terrorist attacks. He expressed gratitude for the brave first responders, military members, and ordinary Americans who showed courage and saved lives on that day. The President also mentioned the strength, courage, and compassion displayed by Americans in the aftermath of the attacks. He highlighted the Permanent Authorization of the September 11th Victim Compensation Fund Act, which provides compensation to victims and their families, first responders, and those involved in rescue and recovery operations. The proclamation called for prayers for survivors, families, members of the Armed Forces, and first responders. President Trump proclaimed September 11, 2019, as Patriot Day and called for the flag of the United States to be displayed at half-staff. He invited governors, organizations, and individuals to join in observance and encouraged participation in community service and remembrance ceremonies. The proclamation also called for a moment of silence at 8:46 a.m. Eastern Daylight Time to honor the innocent victims of the attacks.